This 1 Question, 1 Answer AI Quiz method is:
✅ Active Learning – You engage directly with each question.
✅ Immediate Feedback – You get instant explanations and corrections.
✅ Pattern Recognition – You start to see grammar rules in action.
✅ Memory Reinforcement – Repeated exposure locks in the knowledge.

Since TOEIC is a pattern-based test, this interactive, focused training is one of the most effective ways to improve grammatical accuracy and speed. 🚀


Here is the translated version of your **TOEIC 100 Essential Grammar Patterns & Sample Phrases** in English.

Ask me one question at a time about modal verbs. Wait for my answer before responding. If correct, say "✅ Correct!" and continue. If wrong, say "❌ Incorrect!" and give the right answer. Stop when I say "stop."



---

* ## **🔹 1. Tenses**
1️⃣ **Present Simple** – The company **produces** software.  
2️⃣ **Present Continuous** – They **are developing** a new app.  
3️⃣ **Present Perfect** – She **has worked** here for 5 years.  
4️⃣ **Present Perfect Continuous** – We **have been waiting** for 30 minutes.  
5️⃣ **Past Simple** – The meeting **started** at 10 AM.  
6️⃣ **Past Continuous** – I **was talking** when he called.  
7️⃣ **Past Perfect** – They **had already left** when we arrived.  
8️⃣ **Past Perfect Continuous** – He **had been studying** for 3 hours before the test.  
9️⃣ **Future Simple** – I **will send** the email tomorrow.  
🔟 **Future Continuous** – This time tomorrow, I **will be flying** to New York.  

---

* ## **🔹 2. Modal Verbs**
1️⃣1️⃣ **Can (Ability)** – She **can speak** three languages.  
1️⃣2️⃣ **Must (Obligation)** – You **must wear** a seatbelt.  
1️⃣3️⃣ **Should (Advice)** – You **should review** the contract.  
1️⃣4️⃣ **May (Possibility)** – The train **may be** delayed.  
1️⃣5️⃣ **Might (Lower Possibility)** – They **might not come**.  
1️⃣6️⃣ **Could (Polite Request)** – **Could** you help me?  
1️⃣7️⃣ **Would (Hypothetical & Politeness)** – I **would go** if I had time.  
1️⃣8️⃣ **Shall (Formal Suggestion)** – **Shall** we begin?  
1️⃣9️⃣ **Had better (Strong Advice)** – You **had better leave** now.  
2️⃣0️⃣ **Would rather (Preference)** – I **would rather stay** home.  

---

* ## **🔹 3. Conditionals**
2️⃣1️⃣ **Zero Conditional** – If you **heat** water, it **boils**.  
2️⃣2️⃣ **First Conditional** – If it **rains**, I **will stay** home.  
2️⃣3️⃣ **Second Conditional** – If I **had** more time, I **would travel**.  
2️⃣4️⃣ **Third Conditional** – If I **had studied**, I **would have passed**.  
2️⃣5️⃣ **Mixed Conditional** – If I **had saved** money, I **would be** rich now.  

---

## **🔹 4. Passive Voice**
2️⃣6️⃣ **Present Passive** – The report **is written** every week.  
2️⃣7️⃣ **Past Passive** – The contract **was signed** yesterday.  
2️⃣8️⃣ **Future Passive** – The order **will be shipped** tomorrow.  
2️⃣9️⃣ **Present Perfect Passive** – The project **has been completed**.  
3️⃣0️⃣ **Modal + Passive** – The meeting **must be scheduled** soon.  

---

## **🔹 5. Comparisons**
3️⃣1️⃣ **Comparative (Short Adjective)** – This task is **easier** than expected.  
3️⃣2️⃣ **Comparative (Long Adjective)** – This project is **more challenging** than the last one.  
3️⃣3️⃣ **Superlative (Short Adjective)** – This is the **fastest** route.  
3️⃣4️⃣ **Superlative (Long Adjective)** – This is the **most important** decision.  
3️⃣5️⃣ **Double Comparatives** – The **more** you practice, the **better** you get.  

---

## **🔹 6. Gerunds & Infinitives**
3️⃣6️⃣ **Gerund (Verb + ing)** – She enjoys **reading** business reports.  
3️⃣7️⃣ **Infinitive (to + Verb)** – I need **to complete** this task.  
3️⃣8️⃣ **Gerund after Prepositions** – He is interested **in working** abroad.  
3️⃣9️⃣ **Infinitive after Adjective** – It is important **to arrive** on time.  
4️⃣0️⃣ **Verb + Gerund/Infinitive (Different Meaning)** –  
- I **stopped smoking** (I quit smoking).  
- I **stopped to smoke** (I paused to smoke).  

---

## **🔹 7. Inversions**
4️⃣1️⃣ **Negative Adverb Inversion** – Never **have I seen** such dedication.  
4️⃣2️⃣ **Conditional Inversion** – Should you **need help**, let me know.  
4️⃣3️⃣ **Hypothetical Inversion** – Had I **known**, I would have helped.  

---

## **🔹 8. Relative Clauses**
4️⃣4️⃣ **Relative Adverb Why (Reason)** – This is the reason **why** I left.  
4️⃣5️⃣ **Preposition + Relative Pronoun** – The company **for which** I work is global.  

---

## **🔹 9. Prepositional Phrases**
4️⃣6️⃣ **Purpose** – with a view to improving efficiency  
4️⃣7️⃣ **Means** – by means of online surveys  
4️⃣8️⃣ **Contrast** – as opposed to last year  

---

## **🔹 10. Causative Verbs**
4️⃣9️⃣ **Make (Force/Compel)** – The manager **made** him **work** overtime.  
5️⃣0️⃣ **Have (Request/Arrange)** – She **had** her assistant **schedule** the meeting.  

---

## **🔹 11. Key Prepositions**
5️⃣1️⃣ **Cause** – The event was canceled **due to** the storm.  
5️⃣2️⃣ **Purpose** – He studies **for the purpose of** improving his skills.  
5️⃣3️⃣ **Method** – The letter was written **by hand**.  
5️⃣4️⃣ **Contrast** – **Despite** the rain, we continued.  

---

## **🔹 12. Emphatic Structures**
5️⃣5️⃣ **It is … that …** – It is quality **that matters most**.  
5️⃣6️⃣ **What … is …** – What I **need** is more time.  

---

## **🔹 13. Reported Speech**
5️⃣7️⃣ **Tense Shift** – He said, **"I am busy."** → He said **he was busy**.  
5️⃣8️⃣ **Reporting Requests** – **"Please send the report."** → He asked me **to send the report**.  

---

Here is the **continuation** of the fully translated list:

---

## **🔹 14. Conjunctions (Connecting Words)**
5️⃣9️⃣ **Time Conjunctions** – As soon as he arrived, the meeting started.  
6️⃣0️⃣ **Reason Conjunctions** – He was late because of traffic.  
6️⃣1️⃣ **Contrast & Concession Conjunctions** – Although it was expensive, she bought it.  
6️⃣2️⃣ **Conditional Conjunctions** – If you study, you will pass.  
6️⃣3️⃣ **Hypothetical Conjunctions** – You can go provided that you finish your work.  

---

## **🔹 15. Prepositions**
6️⃣4️⃣ **Cause/Reason** – The event was canceled **due to** the storm.  
6️⃣5️⃣ **Purpose** – He studies **for the purpose of** improving his skills.  
6️⃣6️⃣ **Method** – The letter was written **by hand**.  
6️⃣7️⃣ **Contrast/Concession** – **Despite** the rain, we continued.  
6️⃣8️⃣ **Comparison** – This model is superior **to** the previous one.  
6️⃣9️⃣ **Time** – The event is scheduled **for next Monday**.  
7️⃣0️⃣ **Concession** – **In spite of** the delay, we finished on time.  

---

## **🔹 16. Relative Clauses**
7️⃣1️⃣ **Relative Pronoun Who (People)** – The employee **who won** the award is my friend.  
7️⃣2️⃣ **Relative Pronoun Which (Things)** – The report **which I read** was useful.  
7️⃣3️⃣ **Relative Pronoun That (People & Things)** – The car **that he bought** is expensive.  
7️⃣4️⃣ **Relative Pronoun Whose (Possession)** – She’s the manager **whose office** is on the 3rd floor.  
7️⃣5️⃣ **Relative Adverb Where (Places)** – This is the company **where I work**.  

---

## **🔹 17. Verb Patterns**
7️⃣6️⃣ **Gerund after Verbs** – She enjoys **reading** business reports.  
7️⃣7️⃣ **Infinitive after Verbs** – I need **to complete** this task.  
7️⃣8️⃣ **Different Meaning with Gerund & Infinitive** –  
   - I **stopped smoking** (I quit smoking).  
   - I **stopped to smoke** (I paused to smoke).  
7️⃣9️⃣ **Verb + Infinitive as Object** – She **promised to finish** the project.  

---

## **🔹 18. Passive Voice**
8️⃣0️⃣ **Present Passive** – The report **is written** every week.  
8️⃣1️⃣ **Past Passive** – The contract **was signed** yesterday.  
8️⃣2️⃣ **Future Passive** – The order **will be shipped** tomorrow.  
8️⃣3️⃣ **Modal + Passive** – The meeting **must be scheduled** soon.  

---

## **🔹 19. Comparisons**
8️⃣4️⃣ **Comparative (Short Adjective)** – This task is **easier** than expected.  
8️⃣5️⃣ **Comparative (Long Adjective)** – This project is **more challenging** than the last one.  
8️⃣6️⃣ **Superlative (Short Adjective)** – This is the **fastest** route.  
8️⃣7️⃣ **Superlative (Long Adjective)** – This is the **most important** decision.  
8️⃣8️⃣ **Double Comparatives** – The **more** you practice, the **better** you get.  

---

## **🔹 20. Inversions**
8️⃣9️⃣ **Negative Adverb Inversion** – Never **have I seen** such dedication.  
9️⃣0️⃣ **Conditional Inversion** – Should you **need help**, let me know.  
9️⃣1️⃣ **Hypothetical Inversion** – Had I **known**, I would have helped.  

---

## **🔹 21. Emphatic Structures**
9️⃣2️⃣ **It is … that …** – It is quality **that matters most**.  
9️⃣3️⃣ **What … is …** – What I **need** is more time.  

---

## **🔹 22. Reported Speech**
9️⃣4️⃣ **Tense Shift** – He said, **"I am busy."** → He said **he was busy**.  
9️⃣5️⃣ **Reporting Requests** – **"Please send the report."** → He asked me **to send the report**.  

---

## **🔹 23. TOEIC-Specific Grammar**
9️⃣6️⃣ **Be to Construction** – The CEO **is to announce** the decision tomorrow.  
9️⃣7️⃣ **Phrasal Verbs** – Please **fill out** the form.  
9️⃣8️⃣ **Subject + be + Past Participle + to Infinitive** – The project **is expected to be completed** soon.  
9️⃣9️⃣ **Inversion Structures** – Only after the meeting **did I realize** the mistake.  
🔟0️⃣ **Mixed Tenses** – Since she **left**, I **have been** alone.  

